\n\n{{s-bef|before=(founder)}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[File:Royal arms of Aragon (Crowned).svg|50px]]<br>[[Dynasty|Ruling House]] of [[Kingdom of Aragon|Aragon]]|years=948-1035 (as counts); 1035-1164 (as kings)}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[House of Barcelona]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before=House of Beni Mamaduna}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[File:Coat of Arms of Castile.svg|50px]]<br>[[Dynasty|Ruling House]] of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]]|years=1037 - 1126}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Castilian House of Ivrea]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before=[[Astur-Leonese dynasty|House of Asturias-Le\u00f3n]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[File:Coat of Arms of Le\u00f3n.svg|50px]]<br>[[Dynasty|Ruling House]] of [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]]|years=1037 - 1126}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Castilian House of Ivrea]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Royal houses of Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jimenez Dynasty}}\n[[Category:Medieval Spain]]\n[[Category:House of Jim\u00e9nez| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2016}}\n{{Royal house|\n| surname = Jim\u00e9nez\n| country = {{flag|Navarre}} (Kingdom of Pamplona) (Control lost in 1234)<br>{{flag|Aragon}} (Control lost in 1164)<br>{{flag|Castile}} (Control lost in 1126) <br> {{flag|Le\u00f3n}} (Control lost in 1126) <br> {{flag|Galicia}} (Control lost in 1126)<br>\n| titles = [[Emperor of Spain|Emperor of all Spain]]<br> [[King of Leon]] <br> [[King of Castile]] <br> [[King of Galicia]] <br> [[King of Aragon]] <br> [[King of Pamplona]] <br> [[King of Navarre]] <br> [[King of Viguera]] <br> [[King of England|Queen Consort of England]] <br> [[King of Sicily|Queen Consort of Sicily]] <br> [[Count of Aragon]] <br> Count of the Principate <br> Count of Montescaglioso <br> [[Countess of Champagne]] \n| founder = [[Prince]] [[Garc\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez of Pamplona]]\n| final ruler = [[Sancho VII of Navarre|Sancho VII]]\n| current head = Extinct\n| founding year = 921\n| dissolution = 1234\n| ethnicity =\n| cadet branches =\n}}\n\nThe '''Jim\u00e9nez dynasty''',<ref>[[Roger Collins]], ''The Basques'' (Blackwell, 1986), p. 163.</ref> alternatively called the '''Jimena''', the '''Sancha''', the '''Banu Sancho''', the '''Abarca''' or the '''Banu Abarca''',<ref name=\"Ca\u00f1ada Juste\">Alberto Ca\u00f1ada Juste, \"\u00bfQui\u00e9n fue Sancho Abarca?, ''Pr\u00edncipe de Viana'', 73: 79-132.</ref> were a [[Basques|Basque]] ruling family from the 10th century to the 13th century.\n\n== History ==\nThe first known member of the family, [[Garc\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez of Pamplona]], is obscure, it being stated by the ''[[C\u00f3dice de Roda]]'' that he was \"king of another part of the kingdom\" of Pamplona, presumably lord of part of Navarre beyond the area of direct control of the \u00cd\u00f1iguez kings: probably the frontier areas of [[\u00c1lava]] and the western Pyrenees given the list of their landholdings preserved in a later charter. It was long believed that their origins lay in Gascony.\n\nIn 905 [[Sancho I of Pamplona|Sancho Garc\u00e9s]], a younger son of the dynasty founder, used foreign assistance to displace the \u00cd\u00f1iguez ruler [[Fort\u00fan Garc\u00e9s of Pamplona|Fort\u00fan Garc\u00e9s]] and consolidate the monarchy in his dynasty's hands. He would be viewed as founder of the dynasty, with several [[Al-Andalus|Iberian Muslim]] sources calling the family the ''Banu Sanjo'' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0646\u0648&nbsp;\u0634\u0627\u0646\u062c\u0647}} - the descendants of Sancho) for several subsequent generations, while a 12th-century Tunisian chronicler of Al-Andalus, [[Ibn al-Kardab\u016bs]], would referred to [[Sancho III of Pamplona]] as ''ibn Abarca'' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0646&nbsp;\u0623\u0628\u0631\u0643}} - son or descendant of ''Abarca''), referencing a nickname originally borne by Sancho I in the naming of this ''Banu Abarca'' dynasty.<ref name=\"Ca\u00f1ada Juste\" />  In addition to repulsing several attacks from the [[Emir of C\u00f3rdoba]], Sancho I crushed the neighboring [[Banu Qasi]] and thus expanded Pamplona to the upper [[Ebro River]] valley, as well as incorporating the previously-autonomous [[County of Aragon]] into the realm.\n\nFollowing the death of Sancho in 925, his brother [[Jimeno Garc\u00e9s of Pamplona|Jimeno Garc\u00e9s]] maintained a position of strength, intervening in the politics of neighboring Christian and Muslim states. His death left the crown to his nephew, Sancho's son [[Garc\u00eda S\u00e1nchez I of Pamplona|Garc\u00eda S\u00e1nchez I]], who was still a child.  Originally ruling under the tutelage of his mother, the \u00cd\u00f1iguez descendant Toda Aznar who established a web of political and marital alliances among the Iberian Christian states, he invited the intervention of his cousin [[Abd-ar-Rahman III]] of C\u00f3rdoba to achieve emancipation from his mother.  There followed three generations of defeat and subjugation by the Caliphate. He did create for his younger son a short-lived sub-kingdom centered at Viguera, which lasted for several decades until it was reabsorbed into the Pamplona kingdom.\n\nThe kingdom of Pamplona only reemerged from the Cordoban shadow during the reign of [[Sancho the Great]], who ruled from 1000 to 1035 in Pamplona, but also ruled [[Aragon]], [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]], [[ounty of Ribagorza|Ribagorza]] and eventually [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]] (but not [[Kingdom of Galicia|Galicia]]) by right or conquest. He received the homage of the [[Count of Barcelona]] and possibly of the [[Duke of Gascony]]. After his coronation in Le\u00f3n, he even took up the [[Imperator totius Hispaniae|imperial title over all Spain]]. His vast domains were divided amongst his sons at his death, giving rise to three independent medieval kingdoms each ruled by a Jim\u00e9nez monarch.\n\nThe Kingdom of Navarre, passing to the eldest son [[Garc\u00eda S\u00e1nchez III of Navarre|Garc\u00eda]], was unable to maintain its hegemony, leading to the full independence of Aragon under his illegitimate brother [[Ramiro I of Aragon|Ramiro I]], who had previously taken over the territories of murdered brother [[Gonzalo of Sobrarbe and Ribagorza]]. Younger sibling [[Ferdinand I of Le\u00f3n|Ferdinand I]], then [[Count of Castile]], killed [[Battle of Tamar\u00f3n|in battle]] his nominal overlord the [[Bermudo III|King of Le\u00f3n and Galicia]] in 1037 and thereby inheriting them and bringing them fully into the orbit of his ruling clan. He then defeated Garc\u00eda, achieving a sort of hegemony over his brothers, but again divided his realm among his sons. One of these, [[Alfonso VI of Castile|Alfonso VI]], not only succeeded to the reunited realm of his father, but also conquered Toledo, reclaimed the imperial title and even pretended to rule over both Christian and Moslem Spain.\n\nThe Navarre branch of the dynasty went into eclipse when in 1076 [[Sancho IV of Navarre|Sancho IV]] was assassinated by his siblings, and his cousins Alfonso VI of Castile and [[Sancho Ram\u00edrez]] of Aragon converged and divided the kingdom, with the Aragon ruler gaining the Navarre crown, while ceding western lands to Castile.\n\nThe holdings of the family were briefly reunited when [[Alfonso the Battler]] of Navarre and Aragon married Alfonso VI's daughter [[Urraca of Castile|Urraca, Queen of Castile and Le\u00f3n]], and claimed the imperial title. However, the marriage failed and the kingdoms of Castile and Le\u00f3n passed out of the dynasty, to Urraca's son by a prior marriage. The [[Kingdom of Aragon]] and that of [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]] likewise went their separate ways following Alfonso's death, the former passing to his brother, the latter to a descendant of its original ruling family, with each eventually passing to other dynasties through heiresses: [[Petronilla of Aragon]], who married the ruler of Barcelona and thus united those two realms into the [[Crown of Aragon]]; and [[Blanca of Navarre (daughter of Sancho VI)|Blanca]], sister of [[Sancho VII of Navarre]], whose 1234 death brought Jim\u00e9nez rule to an end.\n\nThe [[Borgias]] of Italy in the 15th century would present a pedigree that traced their ancestry to [[Pedro de Atar\u00e9s]], lord of [[Borja, Zaragoza]], who had been a competitor for the thrones of Navarre and Aragon following the death of Alfonso the Battler. Pedro was a scion of this family, being grandson of [[Sancho Ram\u00edrez, Count of Ribagorza]], illegitimate brother of king Sancho Ram\u00edrez of Aragon. Such a descent would thus have made the Borgias male-line descendants of the Jim\u00e9nez dynasty. However, the descent was a fabrication.\n\n== Rulers ==\n{{see also|Kings of Navarre family tree|l1=Navarre rulers family tree}}\nEmperors in '''bold'''. Date of assumption of imperial title in bold and parentheses.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\n! colspan=2 | Ruler!!Born!!Reign!!Death!!Ruling part!!Consort!!Notes\n|-bgcolor=#acd\n|| ''[[Garc\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez of Pamplona|Garc\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez]]''\n|| [[File:Garc\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez of Pamplona.gif|100px]]\n||c.835\n||c.850-885\n||After 885\n||[[Kingdom of Navarre|Pamplona]]\n||Oneca of [[Sang\u00fcesa]]<br/>two children<br><br/>[[Dadildis of Pallars]]<br>four children\n||Sub- or co-king in a part of [[Pamplona]], durings the rulerships of [[Garc\u00eda \u00cd\u00f1iguez of Pamplona|Garcia I I\u00f1iguez]] and [[Fort\u00fan Garc\u00e9s of Pamplona]].\n|-bgcolor=#acd \n|| [[Sancho I of Pamplona|Sancho I ''Abarca'']]\n|| [[File:Sancho Garc\u00e9s I de Pamplona.jpg|100px]]\n||c.860\n||905-925\n||10 December 925\n||[[Kingdom of Navarre|Pamplona]]\n||[[Toda of Navarre|Toda Azn\u00e1rez of Larraun]]<br>seven children\n||Elected king of Pamplona after Fortun Garc\u00e9s' death.\n|-bgcolor=#acd \n|| ''[[Jimeno Garc\u00e9s of Pamplona]]'' (regent)\n|| \n||c.860\n||925-932/3\n||932/3\n||[[Kingdom of Navarre|Pamplona]]\n||[[Sancha Azn\u00e1rez of Larraun]]<br>no children\n||Brother of Sancho I. In spite of being titled as ''prince'' or ''king'', he was merely regentfor his nephew, Garcia. He also tutored the [[County of Aragon]], whose heiress, An